<%# JSON-LD schemas %>
<%= breadcrumb_schema([
  { name: "Home", url: root_url },
  { name: "Everyday", url: category_url("everyday") },
  { name: "Cost Per Serving Calculator", url: everyday_cost_per_serving_url }
]) %>

<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate cost per serving?", answer: "Add up the cost of all ingredients in the recipe, then divide by the number of servings. For example, if all ingredients cost $18 and the recipe makes 6 servings, the cost per serving is $18 / 6 = $3.00. Include every ingredient, even small amounts of spices and oil, for the most accurate result." },
  { question: "What is a good markup for selling homemade food?", answer: "A standard markup for food businesses is 200-300%, meaning a dish costing $3 to make would sell for $9-12. Higher-end or specialty items can command 400% or more. Baked goods typically have a 100-200% markup. Consider your local market, competition, labor time, and overhead costs when setting prices." },
  { question: "How do I account for ingredient waste in cost per serving?", answer: "Add 10-15% to your total ingredient cost to account for waste, trimmings, and spoilage. For produce-heavy recipes, add 15-20%. For example, a $20 ingredient total with 15% waste becomes $23 effective cost. Divide this adjusted amount by the number of servings for a more realistic cost per serving." },
  { question: "Should I include labor cost in my cost per serving?", answer: "For personal cooking, ingredient cost per serving is sufficient. For a food business, you should also factor in labor time, packaging, utilities, rent, and equipment depreciation. Industry standard is to multiply the ingredient cost by 3-4x to arrive at a menu price that covers all expenses and provides profit." },
  { question: "How can I reduce the cost per serving?", answer: "Buy ingredients in bulk when possible. Use seasonal produce which is cheaper and fresher. Substitute expensive ingredients with more affordable alternatives. Cook in larger batches to spread fixed costs. Reduce waste by planning meals around perishable ingredients. Store leftovers properly to avoid spoilage and get the most servings from each recipe." }
]) %>

